00:28:31.306 --> 00:28:34.280
JENNIFER PAHLKA: So he
spends a lot of time on hold.

00:28:34.280 --> 00:28:36.150
But he understands
the experience

00:28:36.150 --> 00:28:38.884
that people in the
system are getting.

00:28:38.884 --> 00:28:41.383
So the first thing that he did
is, remember that-- actually,

00:28:41.383 --> 00:28:43.730
let me back up here.

00:28:43.730 --> 00:28:46.149
Oh, it doesn't look
like I did the new deck.

00:28:46.149 --> 00:28:47.690
The first thing that
he did is worked

00:28:47.690 --> 00:28:49.710
on a what we call,
Clean, which is

00:28:49.710 --> 00:28:53.220
a five-screen application
for food stamps,

00:28:53.220 --> 00:28:56.270
instead of a fifty-screen
that works really well

00:28:56.270 --> 00:28:58.240
on a basic smartphone.

00:28:58.240 --> 00:28:59.370
Boom.

00:28:59.370 --> 00:29:02.850
So compare that to
what you saw before.

00:29:02.850 --> 00:29:04.590
And you don't have
to print it, exactly.

00:29:04.590 --> 00:29:05.600
Though when they get
it in the office,

00:29:05.600 --> 00:29:08.260
they still print it, which is
something we're working on.

00:29:08.260 --> 00:29:10.270
This is a very simple
way of figuring out

00:29:10.270 --> 00:29:14.490
where you can spend
your EBT cards.

00:29:14.490 --> 00:29:18.520
This is a very simple way that
you can find out the balance.

00:29:18.520 --> 00:29:21.580
You just simply text
in your EBT card.

00:29:21.580 --> 00:29:23.709
We have a very funky thing
going on in the back end

00:29:23.709 --> 00:29:24.750
to figure out what it is.

00:29:24.750 --> 00:29:26.083
And then we text it back to you.

00:29:26.083 --> 00:29:27.667
Boom.

00:29:27.667 --> 00:29:30.250
And connect in such a way that
you don't have to wait on hold.

00:29:30.250 --> 00:29:34.035
So you text in, you text
in your phone number

00:29:34.035 --> 00:29:36.250
to CalFresh to connect,
and it tells you,

00:29:36.250 --> 00:29:38.180
great, I'm going
to call the HSA,

00:29:38.180 --> 00:29:40.300
the Human Services
Agency, for you.

00:29:40.300 --> 00:29:43.320
And when there's someone
who can speak to you,

00:29:43.320 --> 00:29:44.880
it calls you back.

00:29:44.880 --> 00:29:47.820
Now if you don't have unlimited
minutes on your phone,

00:29:47.820 --> 00:29:50.515
as most of those people
don't, this is a big deal.

00:29:50.515 --> 00:29:52.140
And when you're trying
to work two jobs

00:29:52.140 --> 00:29:54.306
and get your kids to school,
it's a really big deal.

00:29:54.306 --> 00:29:55.695
The thing that I
love about this,

00:29:55.695 --> 00:29:58.300
is this did not happen through
the Human Services Agency

00:29:58.300 --> 00:29:59.340
in San Francisco.

00:29:59.340 --> 00:30:00.340
The guys just did this.

00:30:00.340 --> 00:30:02.974
They're We sort of pulled
back into the fold.

00:30:02.974 --> 00:30:04.390
But they were
literally just doing

00:30:04.390 --> 00:30:07.490
this in sort of an
activist capacity.

00:30:07.490 --> 00:30:12.290
But when Jake, who had worked
on this Churn problem with HSA,

00:30:12.290 --> 00:30:14.870
told Leo O'Farrell,
the head of HSA

00:30:14.870 --> 00:30:18.580
in San Francisco about
this Connect product,

00:30:18.580 --> 00:30:20.640
Leo said, that's fantastic.

00:30:20.640 --> 00:30:22.430
One requirement though.

00:30:22.430 --> 00:30:25.640
It has to be my voice
on the line that

00:30:25.640 --> 00:30:28.840
tells the social services
worker to hold the line.

00:30:28.840 --> 00:30:30.880
Or else they will hang up.

00:30:30.880 --> 00:30:33.440
He insisted on saying,
this is Leo O'Farrell.

00:30:33.440 --> 00:30:34.960
I have a client for
you on the line.

00:30:34.960 --> 00:30:37.970
Please hold.

00:30:37.970 --> 00:30:40.900
When we think that people
in government don't care,

00:30:40.900 --> 00:30:41.561
were wrong.

00:30:41.561 --> 00:30:42.060
They do.

00:30:42.060 --> 00:30:43.230
They just need help.

00:30:43.230 --> 00:30:45.400
When you give it to them,
they want to engage.

00:30:45.400 --> 00:30:48.900
They're really an
amazing group of people.

00:30:48.900 --> 00:30:51.100
So these little things,
I think are adding up,

00:30:51.100 --> 00:30:53.705
to something of a better
experience for people

00:30:53.705 --> 00:30:57.300
who have to deal with
government technology.

00:30:57.300 --> 00:31:01.680
I think in California now, we're
making a bit of a difference.

00:31:01.680 --> 00:31:04.280
But we are really still
nibbling at the edges

00:31:04.280 --> 00:31:06.800
of an enormous problem.

00:31:06.800 --> 00:31:09.210
Government IT in this--
this is an old stat.

00:31:09.210 --> 00:31:11.750
I think it's about $180
billion dollars that we're

00:31:11.750 --> 00:31:13.870
spending on government
IT right now.

00:31:13.870 --> 00:31:15.570
And the results
speak for themselves.

00:31:15.570 --> 00:31:18.480
They're just simply not--
we're not getting anywhere

00:31:18.480 --> 00:31:21.610
near $180 billion of value.

00:31:21.610 --> 00:31:25.030
Of course the good news-- the
United States Digital Service,

00:31:25.030 --> 00:31:28.600
the unit of the executive
office president,

00:31:28.600 --> 00:31:31.410
that I went to DC to set
up, is up and running.

00:31:31.410 --> 00:31:33.180
And Mikey Dickerson
is leading it.

00:31:33.180 --> 00:31:36.400
I can't think of a better
person to do this work.

00:31:36.400 --> 00:31:37.970
He'll threaten to punch people.

00:31:37.970 --> 00:31:40.440
And he cares about
the American public.

00:31:40.440 --> 00:31:42.435
They're doing amazing work.

00:31:42.435 --> 00:31:44.560
We also publish this United
States Digital Services

00:31:44.560 --> 00:31:47.400
Playbook, that explains
to folks in government

00:31:47.400 --> 00:31:50.230
how you can get better
results, for much less money.

00:31:50.230 --> 00:31:52.530
I spent most of the
time that I was there

00:31:52.530 --> 00:31:54.320
on number four, a
billed services that

00:31:54.320 --> 00:31:56.760
use agile and
iterative practices.

00:31:56.760 --> 00:32:01.400
Because the Office of
Federal Procurement Policy,

00:32:01.400 --> 00:32:05.020
that manages Federal
Acquisition Regulation,

00:32:05.020 --> 00:32:07.800
needed to understand that
this is actually legal.

00:32:07.800 --> 00:32:11.110
And so in conjunction with
the Digital Services Playbook,

00:32:11.110 --> 00:32:13.550
we also published something
called the TechFAR Handbook,

00:32:13.550 --> 00:32:15.640
that tells contacting
officers and others who

00:32:15.640 --> 00:32:18.120
work in the field
of procurement,

00:32:18.120 --> 00:32:22.460
why this is legal, how to do
it, and make sure they're very

00:32:22.460 --> 00:32:25.722
clear that at the
end of the day,

00:32:25.722 --> 00:32:27.930
the authority on procurement
is the Office of Federal

00:32:27.930 --> 00:32:29.100
Procurement Policy.

00:32:29.100 --> 00:32:32.210
And when they put this
out that literally says,

00:32:32.210 --> 00:32:34.720
we are helping you
build digital services

00:32:34.720 --> 00:32:37.460
with a particular focus on how
to use contractors to support

00:32:37.460 --> 00:32:39.890
an iterative customer-driven
software development

00:32:39.890 --> 00:32:43.660
process, as is routinely done
in the private sector, that's

00:32:43.660 --> 00:32:44.466
change.

00:32:44.466 --> 00:32:45.840
It's going to take
us a long time

00:32:45.840 --> 00:32:47.587
to see the results
of that change.

00:32:47.587 --> 00:32:49.170
But that's fundamental
change that you

00:32:49.170 --> 00:32:50.270
should be excited about.

00:32:52.990 --> 00:32:57.030
I do want to question the
notion that this is innovation.

00:32:57.030 --> 00:32:58.810
I think this is the basics.

00:32:58.810 --> 00:33:01.170
Government should be able to
ship a website that works.

00:33:01.170 --> 00:33:04.000
And we should not wrap it
in the banner of innovation.

00:33:04.000 --> 00:33:07.380
It sort of degrades the notion
of innovation in my book.

00:33:07.380 --> 00:33:08.960
But I do want to
return to this idea

00:33:08.960 --> 00:33:10.250
that government can innovate.

00:33:10.250 --> 00:33:12.458
And I think that the most
innovation that's happening

00:33:12.458 --> 00:33:16.860
isn't in this sort of battle
between the west coast tech

00:33:16.860 --> 00:33:19.920
wizards and the east coast
protectors of the way

00:33:19.920 --> 00:33:21.070
it used to be.

00:33:21.070 --> 00:33:23.530
But all around the country.

00:33:23.530 --> 00:33:27.090
This is of map of the
brigades in the United States.

00:33:27.090 --> 00:33:29.140
A Code for America
brigade is a group

00:33:29.140 --> 00:33:32.260
of volunteers who meet
generally on a Tuesday

00:33:32.260 --> 00:33:34.330
night in City Hall.

00:33:34.330 --> 00:33:36.290
They are developers,
they're designers,

00:33:36.290 --> 00:33:38.470
they're just random
citizens who can write,

00:33:38.470 --> 00:33:41.520
whatever-- who work
with their cities

00:33:41.520 --> 00:33:45.050
to make technology better,
and make the citizen

00:33:45.050 --> 00:33:46.060
experience better.

00:33:46.060 --> 00:33:48.720
So they do things like
open data portals,

00:33:48.720 --> 00:33:50.760
and help with open
data policies.

00:33:50.760 --> 00:33:51.760
They will stand up apps.

00:33:51.760 --> 00:33:53.550
They can implement
any of the things

00:33:53.550 --> 00:33:55.180
that I just showed,
for people who

00:33:55.180 --> 00:33:57.505
use food assistance
in their city.

00:33:57.505 --> 00:33:59.450
It's very easily redeployable.

00:33:59.450 --> 00:34:01.040
They're doing a
wide range of things

00:34:01.040 --> 00:34:03.980
that the city
themselves can't do.

00:34:03.980 --> 00:34:06.320
So not only are they
helping the city,

00:34:06.320 --> 00:34:07.730
helping the citizens
of the city,

00:34:07.730 --> 00:34:09.520
but the real impact
that they have

00:34:09.520 --> 00:34:12.840
is that the people in government
see this, and go, wow, maybe

00:34:12.840 --> 00:34:15.303
we could do better.

00:34:15.303 --> 00:34:17.469
There's innovation happening
all around the country.

00:34:17.469 --> 00:34:21.370
This is an example of a project
that the Code for America

00:34:21.370 --> 00:34:24.940
Fellows worked on in Charlotte,
North Carolina this year.

00:34:24.940 --> 00:34:26.850
It's a very quick video.

00:34:26.850 --> 00:34:29.857
But I think of it as
somewhat innovative in a way

00:34:29.857 --> 00:34:31.690
that I kind of think
about Google right now.

00:34:31.690 --> 00:34:34.199
I'm sure there's many, many
more innovative things happening

00:34:34.199 --> 00:34:34.698
at Google.

00:34:34.698 --> 00:34:37.170
But I love that
my phone tells me

00:34:37.170 --> 00:34:39.820
when I'm supposed to leave
for an appointment now.

00:34:39.820 --> 00:34:40.650
I didn't ask it to.

00:34:40.650 --> 00:34:42.100
It just started doing that.

00:34:42.100 --> 00:34:46.060
But that notion of let's
get information to a person

00:34:46.060 --> 00:34:51.090
exactly when they need it is
sort of innovative these days.

00:34:51.090 --> 00:34:53.257
And so the folks in
Charlotte asked our team

00:34:53.257 --> 00:34:55.465
to build something that
looks a little bit like-- oh,

00:34:55.465 --> 00:34:56.340
I have to click this.

00:34:56.340 --> 00:34:57.160
Sorry about that.

00:34:57.160 --> 00:35:00.495
You select the kind of thing
you want notifications about,

00:35:00.495 --> 00:35:04.040
and then in the next screen, it
gives you a map of your city.

00:35:04.040 --> 00:35:09.560
And you can custom draw whatever
geography is relevant to you.

00:35:09.560 --> 00:35:11.730
So you may want to know
about special events

00:35:11.730 --> 00:35:13.340
across the whole city.

00:35:13.340 --> 00:35:16.560
You may want to know
about new businesses just

00:35:16.560 --> 00:35:19.117
on the three blocks
right where you live.

00:35:19.117 --> 00:35:19.950
It lets you do that.

00:35:19.950 --> 00:35:21.700
And then asks for your
cellphone or email,

00:35:21.700 --> 00:35:23.760
and it texts you or
emails you when there's

00:35:23.760 --> 00:35:26.510
a traffic incident, or a
water service, or whatever,

00:35:26.510 --> 00:35:28.890
just in the area that
you've written about,

00:35:28.890 --> 00:35:29.885
that you've defined.

00:35:32.405 --> 00:35:34.030
Here's a great thing--
and I'm actually

00:35:34.030 --> 00:35:36.830
going to try to go over
and demo it for you.

00:35:36.830 --> 00:35:38.730
A bunch of Fellows
this year decided

00:35:38.730 --> 00:35:45.610
that we need to have a much more
broad dialogue about transit,

00:35:45.610 --> 00:35:47.659
especially here
in San Francisco.

00:35:47.659 --> 00:35:49.950
And they built something that
really looks like a tool.

00:35:49.950 --> 00:35:52.370
I'm gonna demonstrate it
for you really quickly.

00:35:52.370 --> 00:35:53.530
You can load up any city.

00:35:53.530 --> 00:35:55.000
I'll use San Francisco here.

00:35:55.000 --> 00:35:57.410
But just hit start.

00:35:57.410 --> 00:36:01.087
And you can draw any
transit line you want.

00:36:01.087 --> 00:36:02.920
So you're going to put
in your transit line.

00:36:02.920 --> 00:36:03.830
I zoomed out.

00:36:03.830 --> 00:36:06.070
So this is a very short line.

00:36:06.070 --> 00:36:09.360
And it'll tell you how much
it costs per year-- sorry,

00:36:09.360 --> 00:36:11.590
now I've got to stop.

00:36:11.590 --> 00:36:13.480
And basically people
all over the country

00:36:13.480 --> 00:36:15.555
have been using this.

00:36:15.555 --> 00:36:18.380
Let me see if I have-- oh,
I didn't put in an example.

00:36:18.380 --> 00:36:21.010
They're making transit maps
the way they want them to be,

00:36:21.010 --> 00:36:21.970
all over the country.

00:36:21.970 --> 00:36:23.200
And in fact, they're
competitive about it.

00:36:23.200 --> 00:36:25.210
In Seattle, is in these
people's are competing

00:36:25.210 --> 00:36:28.100
to do better transit map you
could just load the current map

00:36:28.100 --> 00:36:31.620
and then add it or you can
start with your own lines.

00:36:31.620 --> 00:36:33.920
But it's something that
really, when it came out,

00:36:33.920 --> 00:36:36.150
these sort of urbanist
publications picked it up.

00:36:36.150 --> 00:36:38.000
And they talked about
it as a toy or a game.

00:36:38.000 --> 00:36:40.590
And it is, it's really fun to
play-- not that I showed that

00:36:40.590 --> 00:36:42.140
very well.

00:36:42.140 --> 00:36:44.284
But what we found is
that actually, especially

00:36:44.284 --> 00:36:46.200
in small cities around
the country-- remember,

00:36:46.200 --> 00:36:49.720
there are 30,000 municipalities
in this country--

00:36:49.720 --> 00:36:52.790
it has become, in just a few
short months, the tool they

00:36:52.790 --> 00:36:53.300
are using.

00:36:53.300 --> 00:36:56.140
The enterprise tool that
small cities are using.

00:36:56.140 --> 00:36:59.930
It's displacing--
it's just displacing,

00:36:59.930 --> 00:37:04.430
really in many cases, these
enormous spreadsheets that

00:37:04.430 --> 00:37:05.510
grow up over time.

00:37:05.510 --> 00:37:09.260
But also these enterprise tools.

00:37:09.260 --> 00:37:12.220
So I do see signs of true
innovation in government.

00:37:12.220 --> 00:37:13.250
There's many, many more.

00:37:13.250 --> 00:37:14.791
I'm not going to go
into all of them,

00:37:14.791 --> 00:37:16.300
with the time that we have.

00:37:16.300 --> 00:37:18.210
But I will return
to this notion,

00:37:18.210 --> 00:37:20.050
that it's not just
about this idea

00:37:20.050 --> 00:37:23.790
of for the people from
the "Gettysburg Address."

00:37:23.790 --> 00:37:27.550
But it really is, when you look
at people like Mikey and Jake,

00:37:27.550 --> 00:37:28.400
who are doing this.

00:37:28.400 --> 00:37:29.960
They're doing it
because government

00:37:29.960 --> 00:37:33.980
can work for people--
real people who

00:37:33.980 --> 00:37:35.877
need to interact with
government, and not

00:37:35.877 --> 00:37:36.460
just the poor.

00:37:36.460 --> 00:37:38.084
We all have to interact
with government

00:37:38.084 --> 00:37:39.360
at some point in our lives.

00:37:39.360 --> 00:37:41.590
And when you think
about the people,

00:37:41.590 --> 00:37:43.060
it becomes much more real.

00:37:43.060 --> 00:37:47.800
And of course, by actual real
people who are doing this work.

00:37:47.800 --> 00:37:50.230
The other way that
I really stress

00:37:50.230 --> 00:37:53.340
we must think about this,
is without that middle.

00:37:53.340 --> 00:37:57.260
Government can work
if we make it so.

00:37:57.260 --> 00:38:00.280
It's only going to happen, if
we come together and actually do

00:38:00.280 --> 00:38:04.720
it, which is why I will
and on an ask to you.

00:38:04.720 --> 00:38:06.420
We are just a
couple of years old.

00:38:06.420 --> 00:38:08.325
We've gotten amazing
support for the work

00:38:08.325 --> 00:38:09.330
that we've done so far.

00:38:09.330 --> 00:38:14.450
But there is so incredibly
much more that we need to do.

00:38:14.450 --> 00:38:16.400
The first thing I would
ask Googlers to do

00:38:16.400 --> 00:38:18.910
is to-- and excuse me,
because I know that recruiting

00:38:18.910 --> 00:38:21.550
is difficult all
over the Valley,

00:38:21.550 --> 00:38:24.155
and all over the tech
industry-- but take a year off

00:38:24.155 --> 00:38:26.086
and do this with us.

00:38:26.086 --> 00:38:27.710
Our Code for America
Fellowship program

00:38:27.710 --> 00:38:28.835
is a year out of your life.

00:38:28.835 --> 00:38:31.160
We've had I think four
Googlers do it so far.

00:38:31.160 --> 00:38:32.720
We'd like to have 40 more do it.

00:38:32.720 --> 00:38:35.040
We'd like to have
400 more do it.

00:38:35.040 --> 00:38:36.670
It's an amazing experience.

00:38:36.670 --> 00:38:38.740
You will learn and
do, and see things

00:38:38.740 --> 00:38:40.710
that you would never
thought you would do.

00:38:40.710 --> 00:38:43.320
[INAUDIBLE], who did
it two years ago,

00:38:43.320 --> 00:38:46.700
ended up learning a lot about
the criminal justice system.

00:38:46.700 --> 00:38:50.450
And that's something I
could do a whole talk on.

00:38:50.450 --> 00:38:52.170
It's a fantastic experience.

00:38:52.170 --> 00:38:54.940
And our 2015 class
is already set.

00:38:54.940 --> 00:38:56.780
So the next opportunity
would for you

00:38:56.780 --> 00:38:59.912
to apply in the middle
of 2015 for 2016.

00:38:59.912 --> 00:39:01.620
But I would love to
talk to you about it,

00:39:01.620 --> 00:39:04.950
if it's something you'd
be interested in doing.

00:39:04.950 --> 00:39:08.040
We're able to do our work
because the tech industry has

00:39:08.040 --> 00:39:09.450
done very well for itself.

00:39:09.450 --> 00:39:11.920
And we hope that people
will consider donating,

00:39:11.920 --> 00:39:13.490
so that we can do
more of this work

00:39:13.490 --> 00:39:15.690
for the people who need it.

00:39:15.690 --> 00:39:18.640
It's not the only way that
you can get involved though.

00:39:18.640 --> 00:39:22.280
We recently-- well, we did not
launch-- Ron Bouganim recently

00:39:22.280 --> 00:39:26.430
launched the first
ever Govtech fund.

00:39:26.430 --> 00:39:29.520
It's a venture fund just for
companies that are actually

00:39:29.520 --> 00:39:33.160
going to disrupt in a good
way, the civic ecosystem,

00:39:33.160 --> 00:39:35.862
or government
technology ecosystem.

00:39:35.862 --> 00:39:37.320
So I would encourage
any of you who

00:39:37.320 --> 00:39:39.150
are thinking about
doing businesses,

00:39:39.150 --> 00:39:42.740
to look at that
$180 billion market.

00:39:42.740 --> 00:39:45.500
A lot of that is going to
change over the coming years.

00:39:45.500 --> 00:39:49.220
And the companies that are going
in there to offer services,

00:39:49.220 --> 00:39:51.350
that look like the kind
of work that you do here,

00:39:51.350 --> 00:39:53.754
are going to be
extremely successful.

00:39:53.754 --> 00:39:55.170
There's also
obviously opportunity

00:39:55.170 --> 00:39:57.370
to invest in
companies like that.

00:39:57.370 --> 00:40:00.410
And then there's a million
sort of casual ways

00:40:00.410 --> 00:40:01.830
that you can help.

00:40:01.830 --> 00:40:04.240
On our site right now, you
can find our civic tech issue

00:40:04.240 --> 00:40:04.750
finder.

00:40:04.750 --> 00:40:08.800
So if you wanted to go, say,
take an hour tonight and code

00:40:08.800 --> 00:40:13.067
on a project that has an open
issue across our network--

00:40:13.067 --> 00:40:15.150
which includes not just
Code for America projects,

00:40:15.150 --> 00:40:16.650
but across the civic
tech ecosystem.

00:40:16.650 --> 00:40:20.410
So Sunlight Foundation
has projects on there.

00:40:20.410 --> 00:40:21.910
You can pretty
easily find something

00:40:21.910 --> 00:40:22.993
that might need your help.

00:40:22.993 --> 00:40:25.970
Do a little help, and
feel good about yourself.

00:40:25.970 --> 00:40:28.260
But to me-- and whatever
you do, the point is,

00:40:28.260 --> 00:40:31.960
we are all told every day that
we are primarily consumers,

00:40:31.960 --> 00:40:34.120
that our job is to buy things.

00:40:34.120 --> 00:40:36.110
But we really have to
live like citizens.

00:40:36.110 --> 00:40:38.110
And understanding that
your government needs you

00:40:38.110 --> 00:40:40.300
is part of that.

00:40:40.300 --> 00:40:42.438
Thank you very
much for having me.

00:40:42.438 --> 00:40:46.230
