that's not an excuse

00:44:52.830 --> 00:44:55.530
not to help the people in
our country who need help.

00:44:55.530 --> 00:44:57.220
AUDIENCE: One question
from the Dory.

00:44:57.220 --> 00:45:00.540
Jonathan Betts is asking,
how can lessons-- sorry,

00:45:00.540 --> 00:45:03.610
I should-- how can lessons
learned through experiences

00:45:03.610 --> 00:45:06.780
like Healthcare.gov scale
across all people and government

00:45:06.780 --> 00:45:07.971
responsible for technology?

00:45:07.971 --> 00:45:10.220
JENNIFER PAHLKA: I think
there's two levels of answer.

00:45:10.220 --> 00:45:13.420
And the first one is, the
Digital Services Playbook--

00:45:13.420 --> 00:45:14.890
and I showed a
screenshot of it--

00:45:14.890 --> 00:45:18.254
is the lessons learned
from Healthcare.gov.

00:45:18.254 --> 00:45:20.170
Well, and from every
other technology project.

00:45:20.170 --> 00:45:21.900
But the failure
of Healthcare.gov

00:45:21.900 --> 00:45:26.470
gave that a lot more prominence,
and a lot more political

00:45:26.470 --> 00:45:30.680
power, than it would have if
we hadn't just had that crisis.

00:45:30.680 --> 00:45:33.490
So the Playbook is now there.

00:45:33.490 --> 00:45:34.490
It's a good playbook.

00:45:34.490 --> 00:45:36.780
I think somebody on O'Reilly
Radar wrote it up as,

00:45:36.780 --> 00:45:40.050
'not a playbook not just for
government, any private sector

00:45:40.050 --> 00:45:42.790
company should
follow this playbook.

00:45:42.790 --> 00:45:45.180
The problem is that you
can know what to do.

00:45:45.180 --> 00:45:46.680
You can know what's
right, and still

00:45:46.680 --> 00:45:48.560
have challenges
within a culture,

00:45:48.560 --> 00:45:51.470
in a bureaucracy that's done
it differently for a long time.

00:45:51.470 --> 00:45:54.010
And so in order
for those practices

00:45:54.010 --> 00:45:58.130
to actually scale in
practice-- can I say that?

00:45:58.130 --> 00:46:00.240
The practices of
scale in practice--

00:46:00.240 --> 00:46:02.730
we need to support the
people in government

00:46:02.730 --> 00:46:04.820
who run into obstacles.

00:46:04.820 --> 00:46:09.595
And so Mikey's team is basically
piloting a way to do that.

00:46:09.595 --> 00:46:13.940
That then they can take-- each
time they run into an obstacle,

00:46:13.940 --> 00:46:17.220
whether it's a legal obstacle,
a [INAUDIBLE] obstacle, an HR

00:46:17.220 --> 00:46:19.770
obstacle-- they're figuring out
how to sort of blow that up.

00:46:19.770 --> 00:46:22.490
And then documenting
how they blew that up,

00:46:22.490 --> 00:46:24.140
and then getting that out there.

00:46:24.140 --> 00:46:25.930
So what's that great line?

00:46:25.930 --> 00:46:27.760
The difference between
theory and practice

00:46:27.760 --> 00:46:30.095
is always greater in theory
that it is in practice?

00:46:30.095 --> 00:46:31.790
Did I say that right?

00:46:31.790 --> 00:46:33.680
Practice than it is in-- OK.

00:46:33.680 --> 00:46:37.720
Point is the recipe is there.

00:46:37.720 --> 00:46:40.270
It's going to take a long time
before people are actually

00:46:40.270 --> 00:46:42.560
following it.

00:46:42.560 --> 00:46:44.960
And that's where,
again-- thank you

00:46:44.960 --> 00:46:46.460
for the setup
question, Jonathan.

00:46:46.460 --> 00:46:48.520
It comes back to,
it doesn't work

00:46:48.520 --> 00:46:50.780
if you don't have
people who know

00:46:50.780 --> 00:46:54.520
how to build digital
services that way there.

00:46:54.520 --> 00:46:59.080
And don't accept a different
way of doing things.

00:46:59.080 --> 00:47:00.134
And can normalize it.

00:47:00.134 --> 00:47:01.800
And can say, well,
we won't-- you know--

00:47:01.800 --> 00:47:03.530
I know that seems radical here.

00:47:03.530 --> 00:47:06.710
But that really is how effective
digital services are built,

00:47:06.710 --> 00:47:07.477
I guarantee it.

00:47:07.477 --> 00:47:09.810
Then it makes people feel a
little bit more comfortable.

00:47:09.810 --> 00:47:13.854
So we have to have the people
there to back up the playbook.

00:47:13.854 --> 00:47:15.770
AUDIENCE: Working with
San Francisco is great.

00:47:15.770 --> 00:47:17.814
And there's people
around here, at Google

00:47:17.814 --> 00:47:18.980
who will come help out.

00:47:18.980 --> 00:47:21.230
But how do you scale this
to sort of local governments

00:47:21.230 --> 00:47:22.270
around the country?

00:47:22.270 --> 00:47:22.990
There's so many.

00:47:22.990 --> 00:47:24.531
And there's just
really not like-- it

00:47:24.531 --> 00:47:28.107
seems like not enough tech
talent to take this abroad.

00:47:28.107 --> 00:47:29.440
JENNIFER PAHLKA: Thank you, yes.

00:47:29.440 --> 00:47:31.580
So the question of scaling
it to local governments

00:47:31.580 --> 00:47:33.290
is what we spend
most of our time on.

00:47:33.290 --> 00:47:34.915
Here, I'll hold it
for the next person.

00:47:34.915 --> 00:47:35.490
Thanks.

00:47:35.490 --> 00:47:38.820
So Steph mentioned our summit.

00:47:38.820 --> 00:47:44.110
So the plan has been basically,
show what's possible.

00:47:44.110 --> 00:47:46.170
Spread the stories
of what's possible.

00:47:46.170 --> 00:47:47.784
Get more people interested.

00:47:47.784 --> 00:47:50.200
And then give them the tools
to solve the problem as well.

00:47:50.200 --> 00:47:54.490
But they first have to believe
that the old way is not

00:47:54.490 --> 00:47:55.220
necessary, right?

00:47:55.220 --> 00:47:57.400
That there's a better
way, and that it's doable.

00:47:57.400 --> 00:48:01.360
And so we've been working
really hard on that.

00:48:01.360 --> 00:48:04.420
Our Fellowship program itself
doesn't scale very well.

00:48:04.420 --> 00:48:06.510
It's extremely intense.

00:48:06.510 --> 00:48:08.680
What we can do though is
scale the outputs of it.

00:48:08.680 --> 00:48:10.555
And so we've built a
series of other programs

00:48:10.555 --> 00:48:13.940
that do that, including a
network of people in government

00:48:13.940 --> 00:48:16.930
who sort of have
drunk the Kool-Aid.

00:48:16.930 --> 00:48:18.690
Then we need to
empower them, to help

00:48:18.690 --> 00:48:22.050
them pilot these things
in their own cities.

00:48:22.050 --> 00:48:25.550
And in that essentially is
the play that we're running.

00:48:25.550 --> 00:48:28.030
It gets a little bit more
sophisticated every year.

00:48:28.030 --> 00:48:30.920
And it gets more sophisticated,
because we get more resources.

00:48:30.920 --> 00:48:34.780
We have been a very,
very small organization.

00:48:34.780 --> 00:48:37.370
Now we're about
almost at 40 people.

00:48:37.370 --> 00:48:39.537
We could easily be 4,000
people, and we still

00:48:39.537 --> 00:48:40.870
wouldn't have fixed the problem.

00:48:40.870 --> 00:48:42.400
But we'll get there.

00:48:42.400 --> 00:48:44.780
Because it's about
building the network.

00:48:44.780 --> 00:48:46.090
It's not just us, right?

00:48:46.090 --> 00:48:47.774
It's the people in
government who do it.

00:48:47.774 --> 00:48:49.940
AUDIENCE: You mentioned the
criminal justice system.

00:48:49.940 --> 00:48:50.840
JENNIFER PAHLKA: Mm hm.

00:48:50.840 --> 00:48:51.730
AUDIENCE: And I think
it's, right now,

00:48:51.730 --> 00:48:53.188
it's kind of an
interesting tipping

00:48:53.188 --> 00:48:54.670
point in the public
consciousness,

00:48:54.670 --> 00:48:57.950
about what-- about
reform, and I'm actually

00:48:57.950 --> 00:49:01.180
working with a nonprofit
that's looking at helping--

00:49:01.180 --> 00:49:03.820
or has specifically
asked Googlers or tech

00:49:03.820 --> 00:49:06.620
people, to open up
some of the tracking

00:49:06.620 --> 00:49:10.200
that we do for people that are
in the criminal justice system.

00:49:10.200 --> 00:49:11.679
JENNIFER PAHLKA: We should talk.

00:49:11.679 --> 00:49:13.220
AUDIENCE: But anyway,
I was wondering

00:49:13.220 --> 00:49:14.803
since I don't have
a lot of time like,

00:49:14.803 --> 00:49:17.250
is there anything specific in
the criminal justice system

00:49:17.250 --> 00:49:19.010
that you guys are working
on that's exciting?

00:49:19.010 --> 00:49:21.051
JENNIFER PAHLKA: Yeah,
thank you for asking that.

00:49:21.051 --> 00:49:23.480
It's actually the area that
I'm most excited about.

00:49:23.480 --> 00:49:27.010
We have identified three
areas of focus for our work

00:49:27.010 --> 00:49:27.700
next year.

00:49:27.700 --> 00:49:29.574
It doesn't mean we won't
do some other stuff.

00:49:29.574 --> 00:49:33.530
But our Fellowship cities
and Fellows next year

00:49:33.530 --> 00:49:36.130
are going to be focusing
on safety and justice,

00:49:36.130 --> 00:49:38.260
economic development, and
health, which is really

00:49:38.260 --> 00:49:40.520
the human services work, a
continuation of the stuff I

00:49:40.520 --> 00:49:42.560
just showed.

00:49:42.560 --> 00:49:46.280
I have become sort
of outraged I think,

00:49:46.280 --> 00:49:48.710
at the way our criminal
justice system is working.

00:49:48.710 --> 00:49:50.960
And it's absolutely
true that a lot of that

00:49:50.960 --> 00:49:52.790
is due to terrible policy.

00:49:52.790 --> 00:49:56.280
But an enormous amount of
it is due to incompetence

00:49:56.280 --> 00:49:57.790
of the system.

00:49:57.790 --> 00:49:59.455
We can't get people
out of jail--

00:49:59.455 --> 00:50:01.080
you know, people who
are held pre-trial

00:50:01.080 --> 00:50:01.997
that don't need to be.

00:50:01.997 --> 00:50:03.746
There was the article
that you've probably

00:50:03.746 --> 00:50:06.380
seen in The New Yorker about
the young man in New York, who

00:50:06.380 --> 00:50:09.060
spent three-- who went
into Rikers at 16,

00:50:09.060 --> 00:50:12.080
and was held without a
trial for three years.

00:50:12.080 --> 00:50:13.760
A lot of that is
simply the system

00:50:13.760 --> 00:50:16.662
can't just tie it's own
shoelaces in the morning.

00:50:16.662 --> 00:50:18.120
There is an enormous
amount that we

00:50:18.120 --> 00:50:23.070
could do using data to get
people not held pre-trial.

00:50:23.070 --> 00:50:25.530
And there are all sorts of
follow-on effects to that.

00:50:25.530 --> 00:50:27.113
If they're not held,
they're much more

00:50:27.113 --> 00:50:29.590
likely to be not
convicted of the crime.

00:50:29.590 --> 00:50:31.100
There's an enormous
amount that we

00:50:31.100 --> 00:50:34.650
can do to keep people from
getting bench warrants.

00:50:34.650 --> 00:50:36.390
So a bench warrant
is what you get

00:50:36.390 --> 00:50:38.302
if you rode your
bike on the sidewalk,

00:50:38.302 --> 00:50:40.760
and got a little teeny ticket
that shouldn't be a big deal.

00:50:40.760 --> 00:50:42.540
But then you never
followed up on it,

00:50:42.540 --> 00:50:43.600
and you never cleared it.

00:50:43.600 --> 00:50:45.474
And suddenly the next
time you're pulled over

00:50:45.474 --> 00:50:47.420
for something, boom,
you're in jail.

00:50:47.420 --> 00:50:49.570
We have a lot of people
in the criminal justice

00:50:49.570 --> 00:50:53.370
system for very, very petty
crimes that don't need to be,

00:50:53.370 --> 00:50:56.340
if we can just make the
system work a lot better.

00:50:56.340 --> 00:50:59.100
We are interested both in the
public safety side of it--

00:50:59.100 --> 00:51:01.790
how can we make our
communities safer?

00:51:01.790 --> 00:51:06.130
And then how can we make
that system far more just,

00:51:06.130 --> 00:51:08.540
using data?

00:51:08.540 --> 00:51:11.450
We did a jail
management dashboard

00:51:11.450 --> 00:51:13.740
in Louisville,
Kentucky, that actually

00:51:13.740 --> 00:51:16.060
[INAUDIBLE] who was a
Googler that worked on.

00:51:16.060 --> 00:51:17.800
It was sort of
his major project.

00:51:17.800 --> 00:51:20.737
That's now being
redeployed to Denver.

00:51:20.737 --> 00:51:22.320
But it gets at like
this basic problem

00:51:22.320 --> 00:51:25.700
that people literally don't
even know who-- they can't even

00:51:25.700 --> 00:51:30.410
look at who is in
the jails, and manage

00:51:30.410 --> 00:51:33.050
that population in any way.

00:51:33.050 --> 00:51:34.740
We've done these
court date reminders.

00:51:34.740 --> 00:51:39.320
So that people who need to show
up to clear a parking ticket,

00:51:39.320 --> 00:51:41.440
can either just do it
through their mobile phone,

00:51:41.440 --> 00:51:43.139
or can be reminded
that they actually

00:51:43.139 --> 00:51:44.180
need to show up in court.

00:51:44.180 --> 00:51:46.120
So they don't end up
getting a bench warrant,

00:51:46.120 --> 00:51:47.780
and reduce the
number of people who

00:51:47.780 --> 00:51:51.660
are like jamming up the system.

00:51:51.660 --> 00:51:56.210
It is probably, after--
name the top things, NSA,

00:51:56.210 --> 00:52:00.070
and Guantanamo River-- like one
of our biggest national shames

00:52:00.070 --> 00:52:00.570
right now.

00:52:00.570 --> 00:52:03.550
We should be terribly ashamed
of how our criminal justice

00:52:03.550 --> 00:52:04.590
system works.

00:52:04.590 --> 00:52:05.970
And we have to do better.

00:52:05.970 --> 00:52:08.360
So we're going to focus
on that pretty heavily

00:52:08.360 --> 00:52:10.020
in the coming three years.

00:52:10.020 --> 00:52:10.520
Thank you.

00:52:10.520 --> 00:52:12.070
[APPLAUSE]

